         <h1>Alighiero e Boetti, 53, an Artist Who Mixed Disparate Elements </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Alighiero e Boetti , an Italian Conceptual artist who saw his work as a collaboration between different people , cultures and disciplines , died on Sunday at his home in Rome . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 53 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was brain cancer , said Gianenzo Sperone , whose gallery in Rome represented the artist for most of his career . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Boetti was born in Turin in 1940 . <br><blue>5</blue>Largely self-educated as an artist , Mr. Boetti had his first solo exhibition in Turin in 1966 and was briefly associated with the Arte Povera movement . <br><blue>6</blue>Drawn to nontraditional techniques , he soon evolved a more poetic , idiosyncratic vision that brought together such unlikely elements as geography and embroidery , or made extensive use of the common ballpoint pen . <br><blue>7</blue>After traveling to Afghanistan in 1970 , he began having local craftsmen translate various motifs , including big , patchwork-like world maps and invented aphorisms , into dense , embroidered surfaces and , later , into kilim rugs . <br><blue>8</blue>Collaborative artworks so appealed to him that he took " e , " the Italian word for and , as his middle name to suggest two people . <br><blue>9</blue>A List of Rivers His most ambitious project , a version of which was recently acquired by the Museum of Modern Art , is a large embroidered piece titled " The First Thousand Rivers of the World . " <br><blue>10</blue>In characteristically blocky letters , this work spells the names of the world 's 1,000 longest rivers in descending order of length . <br><blue>11</blue>It is based on a list that required more than seven years of research by Mr. Boetti and his first wife , Anne Marie Sauzeau , an art critic , and that is known to many scientists as the Boetti List . <br><blue>12</blue>Mr. Boetti , who had his first New York solo show at the John Weber Gallery in SoHo in 1973 , showed his work throughout Europe and is represented in public collections around the world . <br><blue>13</blue>A large exhibition of his work is planned by the Dia Center for the Arts in Chelsea for October . <br><blue>14</blue>He is survived by his wife , Caterina ; two sons , Giordano and Matteo , both of Rome , and a daughter , Agata , of Paris . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>a list that required more than seven years of research by Mr. Boetti and his first wife , Anne Marie Sauzeau , an art critic</m_str> (11_5) 	<m_str>the Boetti List</m_str> (11_39) 	<br><blue>2(22)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (13_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_23) 	<m_str>the artist</m_str> (3_16) 	<m_str>Mr. Boetti</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_21) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_6) 	<m_str>Mr. Boetti</m_str> (11_16) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_28) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (8_6) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_19) 	<m_str>Boetti</m_str> (12_2) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (8_8) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_6) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_11) 	<m_str>Mr. Boetti</m_str> (5_7) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_21) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (9_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (5_10) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_8) 	<br><blue>3(3)</blue>: <m_str>Rome</m_str> (1_31) 	<m_str>Rome</m_str> (3_14) 	<m_str>Rome</m_str> (14_19) 	<br><blue>4(3)</blue>: <m_str>the world 's</m_str> (10_12) 	<m_str>the World</m_str> (9_36) 	<m_str>the world</m_str> (12_34) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>Turin</m_str> (5_15) 	<m_str>Turin</m_str> (4_6) 	<br><blue>6(3)</blue>: <m_str>his work</m_str> (13_5) 	<m_str>his work</m_str> (12_23) 	<m_str>his work</m_str> (1_11) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
